04551nam a22006975i 9781501721519DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20182000nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017215197 a10.7591/97815017215192doi  a(DE-B1597)514812  a(OCoLC)1083626005  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aHIS0200002bisacsh04a364.1/06/094582231 aFentress, James, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRebels and Mafiosi :bDeath in a Sicilian Landscape /cJames Fentress. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4c©2000  a1 online resource (320 p.) :b3 maps, 18 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations and Maps -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Setting: Sicily before the Mafia -- t2. The 1848 Revolt -- t3. The 1860 Revolution -- t4. 1866: The Sette Mezzo Uprising and the Week’s Republic in Palermo -- t5. Cosche and Mafiusi -- t6. Violent Brotherhoods: The Mafia from 1866 to the Stoppaglieri -- t7. Violent Brotherhoods: The Mafia from 1866 to the Stoppaglieri -- tConclusion -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor centuries, Sicilian "men of honor" have fought the controls of government. Between 1820 and 1860, rebellions shook the island as these men joined with Sicily's intellectuals in the struggle for independence from the Bourbon Kingdom of Naples. This lively account—the first to locate the emergence and evolution of the mafia in historical perspective—describes how those rebellions led to the birth of the modern mafia and traces the increasing influence of organized crime on the island. The alliance between two classes of Sicilians, James Fentress shows, made possible both the revolution and the mafia. Militancy in the ranks of the revolution taught men of honor how to organize politically. Communities then resisted the demands of central government by devising alternative controls through a network of local groups—the mafia cosche.Fentress tells his operatic story of honor and crime from the viewpoint of the Sicilians, and in particular of the great city of Palermo—from Garibaldi's historic arrival in 1860 to the spectacular mafia trials around the turn of the century. Drawing on police archives, trial records, contemporary journalism, and government reports, he describes how enduring political power plus a (richly deserved) reputation for violence helped the mafia secure covert relationships with groups that publicly denounced them. These contacts still protect today's mafiosi from Rome's efforts to eradicate the organization. The history of the mafia is indeed, Fentress shows, the history of Sicily.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCrimezItalyzSicilyxHistory. 0aGovernment, Resistance tozItalyzSicilyxHistoryy19th century. 0aMafiazItalyzSicilyxHistory. 0aRevolutionszItalyzSicilyxHistoryy19th century. 4aEurope. 4aHistory. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Italy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150172151940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501721519423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501721519.jpg  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2010  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK